The paper deals with the problem of interpolating signals defined on graphs, which is a topic that falls under the scope of several computer science sub-categories. However, the paper's focus on sparsity and compressibility of graph signals in the Graph Fourier Transform (GFT) domain suggests that it is most likely to be classified under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the use of iterative methods and adaptive thresholding techniques for sparsity-promoting interpolation suggests that the paper may also be relevant to cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis).
